{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654513"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:52:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:52:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18618"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18618"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.05,0.05,0,0.73]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11350"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79494"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11350"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18618"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64816"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"10225"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26344"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26351"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27189"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79494"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe carpometacarpal joint of the thumb has a distinctive shape that enables the complex movements required for opposition of the thumb to other digits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the type of synovial joint found at this site?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ball and socket","Hinge","Pivot","Plane","Saddle"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe carpometacarpal joint of the thumb is a \u003Cstrong\u003Esaddle joint\u003C/strong\u003E where both articular surfaces are reciprocally concave and convex, resembling a saddle and its rider. This configuration allows movement in two planes - flexion/extension and abduction/adduction - enabling the complex movements required for thumb opposition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBall and socket joint\u003C/strong\u003E - Has a spherical head articulating with a cup-like socket, allowing movement in all planes. Examples include the hip and shoulder joints\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPivot joint\u003C/strong\u003E - Allows rotation around a central axis only, as seen in the atlantoaxial joint\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlane joint\u003C/strong\u003E - Has flat surfaces that slide over each other, like the joints between carpal bones\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHinge joint\u003C/strong\u003E - Permits movement in one plane only, like the elbow and interphalangeal joints\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe saddle joint configuration is crucial for the thumb\u0027s ability to oppose other digits, which is essential for precise grip and manipulation of objects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The carpometacarpal joint of the thumb is a saddle joint that allows flexion/extension and abduction/adduction movements.","Saddle joints have reciprocally concave-convex surfaces that articulate like a rider sitting in a saddle.","The unique shape of saddle joints enables complex movements necessary for thumb opposition."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"ite